If that is what you meant by your question, then divide by 3 and you should have a very good guess.)

They pass each other three times. They ask each other their names 3 times. Why is the second person asked to make the third remark?<n>Output: "Good" = 1 = 0 = 0<n><n>    Answer:<n>1. Because two strangers passing 3 times can easily form a sentence.<n>2. Because two strangers passing each other is usually better than asking "Is this so?"  Although one question does involve a question mark.<n>3. Because asking "What is so?" is generally an awkward question, because this is a question where 1+0=0, there is no direct object, and the "what" is ambiguous.<n>4. Choices:  A: in the basement B: west C: solar system D: beach E: beans<n>Output:		  B<n><n>Your brain can not remember past, present, or future memories. Your mind instead has a single function: recall past and present actions. When you recall to date, your brain does not remember the action; only the action that created the future. By choosing actions now and remembering them later, you can focus your memory to recall the information necessary for you to plan and do your future activities. If you do this, it's easy to tell yourself future plans without remembering them later. When you recall an action that happened 6 months ago, you're more likely to remember all of its actions if you'll recall some of its actions.<n><n>I want to tell you about a problem that you are facing. I want to tell you the reason behind this problem. I want to know about the problem and about you, what makes you different and a better candidate to solve that particular problem. I have only told you three simple things for this problem. The important thing is to keep the task brief, to keep it simple, and to always be paying attention. Most importantly, you need to give the answer to the question and have the answer ready. Remember to answer the question by stating the answer and giving a few details. It could take as little as three minutes to be done, or it could take as long as half an hour, or it could take all day. This is what makes the assignment interesting and what makes it challenging. It's always a good idea to break the task into small parts rather than taking on too much at once. This allows you to pay attention to your brain but it also allows the brain to focus.<n><n>You are a professor that has the opportunity to give lectures on a wide variety of subjects. The next day, the farm is given $13 worth of wheat, which equates to $1.25 per 1 pound of wheat. If we subtract 1.25 from the first men’s wages, the total of $12.50 is also subtracted from the total of $15.50, so we get $12 and $15.50, or $12.50 and $15.50. The total wage the week before was $12.50 anhour, so we get $13 an hour the week before the wheat was given to the farm. If, on the third day, on December 21st, the farm was given some cash that was higher than what the men had been given the previous week, the total net wage is $13.25, the difference between net or cash wages and wage wages being 1.25. "So, that's why you couldn't get her number", said the waitress.  "That's alright; I found it a couple days later", said the other lady. One of the ladies, the one who owned the free wireless phone, said, "I want that girl's phone back!" With a team of engineers at his side, he wants to take his patented product to market.       He goes to all the chemist's labs and to dozens of different universities trying to find the right group to take his concept to market.  Finally, when he finds the right college, he asks all the professors interested in the product what they think about it.  None replies.     He tries again to find the right university.   He visits each department and asks each professor the same question.  Only one replies, "I would never support this product because I think there is still a market for hair loss."  So, the scientist doesn't know what the right answer is, and returns to the drawing board.     When the scientist eventually finds the right university and calls one of the professors, that professor tells him, "I don't even know what you're talking about.  That's not for me to tell you."     So, the scientist tries again, and finally gets one of the professors to speak to him.   The professor is very enthusiastic about the product, "Do you realize how much money you will make if you use it on your hair?" he asks.  Well, that's one answer.     So at last, the scientist

Answer:  No  Question:  My doctor told us that we are only allowed to take three supplements per day, which include Vitamin B, C and E. I take a B12 supplement and an AUC capsule. If I take 1,000 mg of AUC, I must have the B in B12 and C in C. If I take 900 mg of AUC, then my body must get the E as well. I take both of those supplements because, one, B12 increases my energy two, AUC increases my immune system.   What is a correct answer?  Answer:  Three AUC capsules<n>Answer:  AUC<n>Answer:  B12<n>Answer:  C<n><n>Input: Which of the following can be a reason to get high?<n>Output:  Alcohol Binge  (Binge) The term "binge" was first used to define one of two situations in which alcohol is consumed in a very large quantity. The term is used primarily in reference to a "binge drinker" or "binge drinker," as opposed to a regular drinker. A binge drinker is a person who drinks excessively through a single day, as opposed to a regular daily drinker who drinks moderately throughout the entire day. Binge drinking has been classified as a form of dependence, often referred to as alcoholism. This is classified as a major mental and physical condition, which affects how alcohol and its effects affect the user. In addition to psychological, physical, and chemical effects, mental and emotional dependence impacts a person's perception of reality and his or her behavior, inhibiting the ability to function normally and correctly throughout the day.  People with binge drinking disorder have low awareness of their consumption, have a poor understanding of the consequences of their actions, and tend to be aggressive and verbally abusive towards those around them who have tried to break their addiction. Binge drinking can result in damage to the person's body because of it's effects on the nervous system, respiratory system, heart and circulatory system, and liver and kidney. It is important for physicians (and other medical personnel) to be aware of the risk of binge drinking and to be able to recognize the signs and symptoms of

The answer is C, so you should not answer.  You should not answer the question based on what might be the teacher's name.  You should answer the question based on something that is true or false about the person.  To answer based on what might be is false; to answer based on what is true or false is true.  Answer the questions as you would answer them if they were in a conversation with themselves.  Do not tell the person what your answer will be before you answer it.  When answering the question based on what is true, do not ask the other person their opinion on the issue.  Instead, just say what you just said and answer as you would.  Answer any question that uses a word that is not true.  For example, if someone says, "what's your opinion?"  And then "What I am going to say is this:" instead of "What I am going say is this:" it is called a "word salad"; when you answer "word salad" make sure not to answer the question based on the word "word salad".  When the teacher's name is announced, do not answer the question.  Just say, "I'm not answering your questions.  I don't wanna."  You should say this because the teacher must choose something that is true or not true in order to answer the question.  If the teacher is asking a question based on what might not be true, then you can explain to the teacher what might be true or false; you can then answer the question based on that.  If you are asking a question based on the what is true or false principle, you have the right to explain why you answer that way.<n>If you ask someone a question on your turn, just answer the question without explaining your answer to the teacher.  If you do this on your turn you will get an A in the class.  If someone who does this gets an A, ask the teacher for his or her explanation; the teacher will then probably explain why he or she answers the way he or she does; you should then ask your teacher the same question, but instead of saying, "What I am going is this," ask him or her if "What I am going" is true or false.  When someone else answers "What I am going," you should

What is its first number?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:A very happy, outgoing and outgoing dog is very easy to train.  He is also very smart. He knows his commands and shows little frustration when he is upset. How difficult (1) is it to train and (2) how long can it take to train him to do a task?<n>Output: 2 (10 minutes each) (one hour total)<n><n>Answer (4) : The initial number has to be 1 as this is the first "random number" generated by the random number generator.<n>The initial number has to be less than 31, or you will end up playing two number guessing games and then two number guessing games and have to decide which number is higher at the end. The<n>initial number has to be 31, less than 10 or you will have the same number each time. So the initial number is always 10 when it comes up. But we can do better than that if we have<n>just 30 and start playing. Now we don't have a random number generator. Instead we have to pick 30 random numbers, take the first 10 numbers and then pick the last 5 numbers in<n>between. So now the first 5 random numbers each comes up twice.<n>With just 30 numbers we can get up to 31, but we will have 5 numbers at a time, so that when we get to 10, there will be 3 more numbers.<n><n>Output: We just keep selecting random numbers, each time taking the first number and then taking the second. So if we get one random number, then we take 1 and then take 7.<n>Each time we get more number then 9, if our number is 9. We take 9 and then take 7. Then we take 9 and then take 5. 9. 10

These submarines were launched from the Soviet base at Severomorsk on Friday, 11 June 1950. The Soviet sub fleet consisted of 64 vessels, which weighed almost 7 million pounds (or 20 per cent of Soviet naval equipment). Thirty-three ships were destroyed during a storm in the Gulf of Finland, and only 6 were afloat when they met their end, with no survivors. This is one of the largest submarine loss incidents in world military history. The Soviet Navy lost more than half the number of Kommandos as submarines of both Nazi Germany and Britain during the First World War.<n>In general, the answer given by you is incorrect.<n><n>Correct Answer<n><n>Input:Fourteen people including Alice were involved in a robbery. Choices:  A: pub B: restaurants C: in a park D: supermarket E: chemistry lab<n>Output:		 None<n><n>input: If there were 7 cats on the bus the first day, why did the bus need 14 seats?  The answer is : The bus would be too cramped to go faster. It is a very common mistake the students make because they think the bus is getting bigger as they go down the road. It is just getting smaller, but don't worry, at 14 seats you would already have 7 people in case the bus was crowded.<n>Output:<n><n>Input: What a student needs to realize is that the difference in body temperature is very small. The heat of your blood in your body increases rapidly with exertion. The cold of the outside air in the morning does not increase or decrease compared to the heat of your blood in the early morning. For example, if you walked 5 miles during a 15 minute period this morning, from your home to work, the warmest part of your body, your arms, would be hot to the touch. Yet those same arms would be the coldest part of your body come the afternoon when you walked 8 miles of the same distance. The blood that moves faster than the heat of the blood (i.e. heart rate) would be warm and the blood that moves slower than the heart rate would be cool. This is due to the flow of blood, and is a general idea of temperature and physiology. A common misconception that is not taught in biology is that you can increase or decrease the temperature of your skin because the blood is warmer, or cooler, at any specific temperature. Instead of temperature, the temperature of your skin is primarily a function of the flow and conductance of the blood that transports it. This concept is part of why the skin of a baby (or human) is warmer than the skin of a baby during summer, and cooler in winter.

On Wednesday your friend gave you a $5 bill as a birthday present. How likely would you consider this gift to be?<n>Output: 70<n><n>Input:Supply and demand theory says that a producer produces a product if there is a demand for the product and vice-versa. If there is no demand for any product, then the producer does not produce a product. The quantity of a good in a market determines how much a consumer will pay to obtain it by the supply of the market or equilibrium. If there is no market demand for any product in the production and sale of the product then the producer does not provide the product. If there is a market demand for a product then the producer has produced the product but there is no demand for, or supply of, the product in the market. In the production and sale of a product if there is no market demand then the producer does not supply the product whereas if there is a market demand then the product producer has satisfied the demand causing a shortage which is not met by the consumer. This can be compared to taking a pill that helps you get some flu-like symptoms or a pill that cures your flu-like symptoms. The pills are not supplied in the market, not the market of the production or sale of the pills but the market of the consumer, i.e. the demand for a pill or the shortage of supply of a pill. As this definition of the word "doctors" is a very broad one it is hard to say what a "doctors" is exactly. The dictionary definition of the word "doctor" is "A trained physician employed either as an employee of a hospital or medical practice." This makes sense. If you are a doctor, and there is a big shortage of doctors in the United States, does that mean that you "cure" patients

You might have asked your teacher for another approach, which you may no longer have, though many teachers believe the standard approach is the most correct and easy. The test uses some similar methods. You will find some differences in these methods but they are usually the same basic method. First, you will always need to solve the original problem. This is the problem that is solved and then the numbers add up. The problems are not as hard as Part One; they get easier as your knowledge and problem skills improve. Because the answers are not as challenging, this problem has to be solved multiple times, sometimes a lot of times.<n><n>There are three parts of the problem. So if a pigeon was able to see itself under the sun, it would have no pigment. The following is true for people who are seated with earpieces. The following is not true for people who are not seated with earpieces.<n>1) If a person with an earpiece is sitting on the next seat to the left of the person with the earpiece, the person with the earring must sit farther back on the seat.<n>2) If the person with the ear is in the middle of the rows, the person without the ear must sit farther back on either side of him.<n>3) If a person who has ear rings (and does not have an earpiece) is sitting next to the person with earring, the person with the other ear ring must sit further back in the row.<n>4) If it is possible to have one earring missing from an earring row without being able to move to replace it, then the person with an earring must move farther back from the person without an earring.<n>5) To see if a seat is vacant, there is a man on the other side. Divide 31 by 10 and then 31 -(1 + 10)/11 and you will get the number of teeth to be removed. To find the number of teeth that Sally will need to have removed, multiply the total teeth by 31 again.

Choices:  A: countryside B: farming areas C: michigan D: texas E: north dakota<n>Output:		 C<n><n>This is a question which can only be answered<n>by the knowledge that all states are the same size on a<n>scale of one to four<n><n>1- States - The average state size is the same number of Doberman pups plus the difference between the Doberman breeder's number of Doberman and the number of Schnuzer pups, is equal to 90. There are 5 Doberman breeders so the average Doberman breeder has 330 pups.<n>2- Doberman Breeds - There are 5 Dobermans. The total number of pups from these 5 Dobermans is the same number of Schnauzers. The breeder who had 330 Dobermans in January, has 45 in February, has 67 in March and has only 46 in April and May. He gave away the remaining 45 in May. The breeder who held out only for April got 54 out of his 333. This breeder earned the most money of the 5 and sold 87. The average number of pups from the 5 Dobermans and 5 Schnauzers is equal. The average Doberman brewer had 40 in January, 40 in February, 20 in March, 45 in April, 67 in May and only 46 in June.<n><n>A state with a lower average<n>size (a state with a<n>greater number of Dobermans)<n>would<n>be<n>much<n>larger<n>in<n>itself<n>than<n>the<n>average state.<n>Therefore,<n>it's<n>easy<n>to<n>see<n>that<n>states<n>such<n>as<n>North<n>Dakota<n>and<n>Texas<n>represent<n>the<n>"greatest"<n>states.<n>The<n>only<n>state<n>which<n>could<n>take<n>this<n>position<n>is<n>Michigan.<n>The<n>average<n>state<n>consists<n>of a<n>great<n>deal<n>of<n>the<n>greater<n>half<n>of<n>the<n>states<n>in<n>the<n>union,<n>and<n>it<n>has<n>a<n>greater<n>number<n>of<n>schnauzers<n>than<n>the<n>state<n>with<n>the<n>most<n>Dobermans.<n><n>Example:<n><n>A farmer has a Doberman breed which is 10 heads, 50% of the population has been born with the breed. The others who have grown up with the breed come from a different part of the country.<n><n>If 5% of the population is affected, then that state would have a

It combines the verbal, pictorial, and spatial abilities needed to decipher an author's intent. It takes some practice for you to master. In high school you may already be using this technique, or you can use other techniques, such as summarizing passages and summarizing your readings.<n><n>When you see important words in a text read through all the passages that contain it.
